vim COMMANDS 
======
vim filename
i---for insert mode 
:wq ----save and exit from the file
:x(small x)--- save content of the file and quite
dd --- delete the line
number (2)--- number of lines to delete 
p---to paste 
yy-- to copy
shift G -- tail part from the file
g --- head part from the file

============================
Basic Operations
----------------------------
vim filename - Open a file in Vim.
i - Enter insert mode to edit text.
Esc - Exit insert mode and return to normal mode.
Saving and Exiting
:w - Save the current file.
:wq - Save and exit the file.
:q! - Exit without saving.
:x - Save and exit (like :wq but more concise).
ZZ - Save and exit (in normal mode).
Editing
dd - Delete the current line.
2dd - Delete 2 lines (change 2 to any number for more lines).
x - Delete a single character.
u - Undo the last change.
Ctrl + r - Redo the last undone change.
Copy and Paste
yy - Copy the current line.
2yy - Copy 2 lines (change 2 to any number).
p - Paste below the current line.
P - Paste above the current line.
Navigation
h - Move left.
l - Move right.
j - Move down.
k - Move up.
0 - Move to the beginning of the current line.
^ - Move to the first non-blank character of the line.
$ - Move to the end of the current line.
gg - Go to the beginning of the file.
Shift + G - Go to the end of the file.
:n - Go to line n (e.g., :10 moves to line 10).
Search
/pattern - Search for pattern in the file (forward direction).
?pattern - Search for pattern (backward direction).
n - Jump to the next occurrence of the search pattern.
N - Jump to the previous occurrence.
Visual Mode
v - Start visual mode (to select text).
V - Start line-wise visual mode.
Ctrl + v - Start block visual mode.
Miscellaneous
:set number - Display line numbers.
:set nonumber - Hide line numbers.
:syntax on - Enable syntax highlighting.
:syntax off - Disable syntax highlighting.
:%s/old/new/g - Replace all occurrences of old with new in the file.
:help command - Open help for a specific command (e.g., :help :wq).
